      'THE FRAUD: Prosecutors alleged Kolfage took over $350,000 for personal expenses including a boat ("Warfighter"), luxury SUV, cosmetic surgery, jewelry, and home renovations. Bannon received over $1 million through a nonprofit he controlled.',
      'SHELL COMPANIES: The conspirators routed money through shell companies and fake invoices to hide their self-dealing. They used the nonprofit "We Build the Wall, Inc." to create the appearance of legitimacy while funneling money to themselves.',
      'BANNON ARREST: On August 20, 2020, Steve Bannon was arrested on a yacht belonging to Chinese billionaire Guo Wengui. He was charged with conspiracy to commit wire fraud and money laundering. He pled not guilty.',
      'TRUMP PARDON: On January 19, 2021, his last day in office, Trump pardoned Bannon. The pardon applied only to federal charges. Bannon was later indicted in New York state for the same conduct - state charges Trump cannot pardon.',
      'KOLFAGE SENTENCE: Brian Kolfage pled guilty and was sentenced to 51 months in federal prison. He was ordered to forfeit $17 million and pay restitution. He also pled guilty to tax fraud charges for not reporting the stolen money.',
      'NY STATE CASE: In September 2022, Bannon was indicted in New York on state fraud charges. He faces 5-15 years if convicted. The case proceeds separately from any federal pardon.',
      'THE WALL: Despite $25 million raised, only a small section of barrier was actually built, and it reportedly began failing almost immediately. The fraud exploited donors patriotic desire to support border security.',
