    severity: 'critical',
    category: 'Sexual Crimes',
    date: 'May 9, 2023',
    lastUpdated: 'February 12, 2026',
    summary: 'Journalist E. Jean Carroll accused Donald Trump of raping her in a Bergdorf Goodman dressing room in the mid-1990s. After Trump defamed her by calling her a liar and saying she wasn\'t his "type," she sued. Juries found Trump liable for sexual abuse and defamation, awarding Carroll $88.3 million.',
    content: [
      'THE ASSAULT: Carroll alleged Trump assaulted her in a Bergdorf Goodman dressing room in either 1995 or 1996. She says he pushed her against a wall, pulled down her tights, and raped her. She told two friends at the time.',
      'GOING PUBLIC: Carroll first published her account in New York Magazine in June 2019 as part of a book excerpt. She was one of dozens of women who have accused Trump of sexual misconduct.',
      'TRUMP\'S DENIALS: Trump responded by calling Carroll a liar, saying the assault "never happened," claiming he never met her (despite a photo together), and saying she wasn\'t his "type."',
      'FIRST TRIAL (2023): A jury found Trump liable for sexual abuse (but not rape under NY\'s narrow definition) and defamation. Awarded Carroll $5 million. The judge later clarified the finding was essentially rape under common understanding.',
      'SECOND TRIAL (2024): A damages trial for earlier defamatory statements (made while president) resulted in $83.3 million verdict: $18.3M compensatory, $65M punitive.',
      'TOTAL DAMAGES: Combined awards of $88.3 million, making it one of the largest defamation verdicts against an individual.',
      'APPEALS: Trump has appealed both verdicts. He posted a $91.6 million bond to stay collection during appeal.',
      'PATTERN: Carroll\'s case is part of a pattern of over 25 women accusing Trump of sexual misconduct spanning decades.',
    ],
    tags: ['E. Jean Carroll', 'Sexual Assault', 'Defamation', 'Rape', 'Civil Verdict'],
