      'ALITO TRAVEL: Alito accepted a luxury fishing trip to Alaska from GOP donor Paul Singer, traveling on Singer\'s private jet. Singer has had business before the Court. Alito did not recuse from cases involving Singer\'s hedge fund.',
      'ALITO FLAG: After January 6, an upside-down American flag - a "Stop the Steal" symbol - flew at Alito\'s home. Another provocative flag flew at his beach house. Alito blamed his wife. He refuses to recuse from January 6 cases.',
      'NO BINDING CODE: Unlike every other federal judge, Supreme Court justices are not bound by the Code of Conduct for Federal Judges. They decide for themselves whether to recuse. There is no enforcement.',
      'ADOPTED CODE: Under pressure, the Court adopted a code of conduct in November 2023 - but explicitly stated it codified existing practices and created no enforcement mechanism. Critics called it toothless.',
      'RECUSAL DECISIONS: Each justice decides unilaterally whether to recuse. There is no review, no appeal, and no transparency. A justice can participate in cases where they have obvious conflicts.',
      'THOMAS-GINNI CONFLICT: Despite Ginni Thomas\'s involvement in the January 6 coup attempt, Clarence Thomas refuses to recuse from January 6 cases. He was the lone dissenter in Trump v. Thompson.',
      'FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE: Justices are required to file financial disclosures but enforcement is minimal. Thomas\'s disclosure violations continued for decades without consequence.',
      'SENATE INACTION: Senate Republicans have blocked legislation to strengthen Supreme Court ethics. They voted against bills requiring disclosure and creating recusal standards.',
      'PUBLIC TRUST: Polls show confidence in the Supreme Court at historic lows. The combination of partisan decisions and ethics scandals has damaged the institution\'s legitimacy.',
      'COURT PACKING DEBATE: The ethics crisis has renewed debate about Court reform - term limits, ethics enforcement, or expanding the Court. The status quo appears unsustainable.',
      'MEDIA ACCESS: The Court\'s public information office has become more restrictive. Justices grant friendly interviews while avoiding scrutiny. Transparency has declined.',
