      'ALBERTO GONZALES: Attorney General Gonzales initially claimed firings were performance-based. Under oath, he claimed not to remember key meetings and decisions, saying "I don\'t recall" dozens of times. His credibility was destroyed.',
      'CONGRESSIONAL INVESTIGATION: Congressional hearings exposed the political nature of the firings. Karl Rove and Harriet Miers refused to testify, claiming executive privilege. Subpoenas were ignored.',
      'WHITE HOUSE INVOLVEMENT: Emails showed Karl Rove and White House Counsel Harriet Miers were involved in selecting prosecutors for removal. The politicization reached into the White House.',
      'GONZALES RESIGNATION: Alberto Gonzales resigned in August 2007 after bipartisan calls for his removal. His testimony was widely viewed as misleading. He left without facing criminal charges.',
      'INSPECTOR GENERAL REPORT: The DOJ Inspector General found the firings were improperly political. But the report noted that lying to Congress and obstruction made full accountability impossible.',
